<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sarajevo Radio Praises Delegation at Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sarajevo Radio Praises Delegation at Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806183094 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1700 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0806183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The position of our delegation toward the peace 
negotiations in Geneva is evidently increasingly gaining trust 
of the international community. A document was signed at the 
talks in Geneva that have just ended aimed at halting the combat 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina -- by which a one-month cease-fire will 
come in force throughout Bosnia-Herzegovina as of noon 10 June. 
  In a statement for the B-H PRESS [news agency] Dr. Ejup 
Ganic, head of the Bosnia-Herzegovina delegation and vice 
president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation, emphasized that 
the delegation had accomplished [words indistinct] set by the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Assembly. We have secured the withdrawal of 
Karadzic's military formations from the 3-km zone around Gorazde 
and afterward an agreement on cessation of combat activities for 
the duration of one month. In this way the aggressor will be 
forced to negotiate a political solution to the clashes in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Dr. Ganic believes. Karadzic tried to 
accomplish a total cease-fire for the duration of at least four 
months in Geneva, which would, on the ground, freeze the 
existing situation and practically mean the recognition of the 
aggressor's conquests. 
  The agreement reached in Geneva is interpreted by the 
international media as a complete success for the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina diplomacy. Our delegation has left open the 
option of extending the cease-fire if the negotiating process 
about the political solution to the Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis 
shows [word indistinct] progress, but rejected meeting the 
aggressor's side in Geneva directly. The talks were carried out 
with the mediation of UN representatives. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

