<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fighting on Brcko Front Continues Unabated </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fighting on Brcko Front Continues Unabated </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0906090794 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 0800 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU0906090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Hamiz Deronjic and Nihad Salihovic] </F>
  [Text] Last night, the chetniks on the Brcko front 
received news of the cease-fire agreement that is supposed to go 
into effect on the Bosnia-Herzegovina fronts at 1200 tomorrow, 
by launching fierce attacks on the defense lines of the free 
Brcko territory. At 2130, a strong 
artillery-reconnaissance-subversive-terrorist group [as heard] 
tried to breach the Brcko defense lines in the Vranovaca region. 
The defenders responded fiercely and the fighting flared up. 
The aggressor ended up with the short end of the stick. 
  After being defeated and suffering losses, the chetniks 
attacked the entire region of Vranovaca from the direction of 
Cadjavac with 82-mm mortars. The final outcome of the fighting 
in Vranovaca is that the (?situation) remained unchanged. 
Between 2000 and 2200, the aggressor attacked the neighboring 
village of Bodariste with 60 and 82-mm mortars from the 
direction of (?Delimir Ravno). During the two-hour artillery 
attack, the enemy fired several dozen shells, but apart from 
destroying more civilian residences, no military successes were 
scored. 
  Overnight, the chetniks intermittently shelled the Zukici 
area with 82-mm mortars from the direction of Sekulici and 
anti-aircraft guns in Lipovac. The aggressor did not accomplish 
his aims on this part of the front either. The defense lines of 
the free Brcko territory are safe and under the full control of 
the fighters of the 108th Motorized Brigade, the 108th Infantry 
Brigade, and units from other contingents. During the agreed 
cease-fire, there are many reasons to remain alert. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

