<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   57 Percent Would Have Voted Against CSFR Split </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    57 Percent Would Have Voted Against CSFR Split </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806124694 Bratislava PRAVDA in Slovak 4 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> AU0806124694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by "ao": "Majority Against Federation's Breakup"] </F>
  [Text] The FOCUS--Center for Social and Marketing Analysis 
agency conducted a public opinion survey from 9 to 23 May 1994, 
in which the organizers involved a representative sample of 
2,018 respondents. One of the questions asked was: "Had a 
referendum been held before the division of the CSFR, how would 
you have voted?" Partition would have been preferred by 27 
percent of those questioned (in October 1993, 23 percent gave 
this reply to the same FOCUS question), 57 percent would have 
voted against partition (60 percent), 11 percent would not have 
participated in the referendum (14 percent), and 5 percent did 
not know (3 percent). Asked what kind of an arrangement of 
relations between the Czech Republic and the Slovak Republic 
they would personally wish in the future, the respondents 
replied as follows: Two independent states would be preferred by 
35 percent (32 percent in October 1993), a confederation or 
union by 30 percent (27), a federal state by 26 percent (35), 
and another arrangement by 3 percent (2). Six percent (4) could 
not decide. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

