<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik Views Possible Arms Deals With Chile </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moravcik Views Possible Arms Deals With Chile </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806185994 Bratislava SMENA in Slovak 6 Jun 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> AU0806185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava SMENA </F>
<F P=105>  Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [TA SR report in the "Day at Home" column: "J. Moravcik on </F>
the Arms Trade"] 
  [Text] Slovakia also has the conditions for becoming 
involved in the arms trade. Prime Minister Jozef Moravcik said 
this in an interview for Radiozurnal in connection with the 
recent visit made by a Chilean military delegation to the Czech 
Republic. In trading in arms, however, Slovakia must proceed 
correctly and in a manner corresponding to its international 
obligations, said the Slovak prime minister. "I do not even 
rule out the possibility of trade with Chile because it is a 
democratic country, and selling arms to this region would not 
harm our foreign policy interests," said J. Moravcik. As far as 
Augusto Pinochet is concerned, Moravcik is aware of the 
complexity of the issue of all that General Pinochet meant in 
Chile's history. First and foremost, it is up to the people of 
this country to come to terms with this issue, added Moravcik. 

</TEXT>

