<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government: Economic Development `Satisfactory' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government: Economic Development `Satisfactory' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806084694 Prague CTK in English 1909 GMT 7 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0806084694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague June 7 (CTK) -- Parliament has received the 
state budget report for the first quarter of 1994 in which the 
government evaluates overall economic development as 
satisfactory. It maintains that social stability is being 
maintained as well as the confidence of foreign investors. The 
influx of foreign portfolio investment amounted to $200 million 
in the first quarter of 1994. 
  The GDP in constant prices grew in the first quarter at an 
annual rate of between 0.5 and two percent. Industrial 
production was down 0.7 percent compared to the first quarter of 
last year. The volume of production of small businesses with up 
to 24 employees was up 23.7 percent compared to the same period 
of last year. 
  Labour productivity expressed in comparable prices was up 
2.7 
percent in industry over the first quarter of last year. The 
average nominal monthly wage was 13.8 percent higher. 
  Overall production in the construction industry was up 6.2 
percent in the first quarter over the same period of last year, 
which the government primarily attributes to enterprises with 
more than 25 workers. 
  Industrial producer prices were up 6.2 percent over the same 
period of last year. The prices of construction work were up 
16.3 percent and agricultural producer prices were up less than 
two percent. 
  The government considers that price increases were moderate 
at the start of the year and correspond to this year's inflation 
forecast of eight to ten percent. Consumer prices rose by 2.4 
percent over the first quarter and by 10 percent compared to the 
same period of last year. Inflationary pressures were gentle 
and corresponded to the growth of demand during a revival of 
economic output. Wage cost inflationary pressures were 
insignificant with regard to the operation of wage regulation. 
  National income was 163 billion crowns in the first quarter. 
Compared to the same period of last year this represents a 
nominal growth of 26 percent and a real growth of 15 percent. 
Nominal incomes from wages grew 14 percent, four percent in 
real terms. Other incomes, the crucial component of which being 
incomes from business activities, increased by 50 percent in 
nominal terms, 37 percent in real terms. Incomes from state 
benefits increased by 30 percent in nominal terms and 18 percent 
in real terms. 
  The population had a net income of 19.6 billion crowns, 
which 
it used to repay loans (1.1 billion crowns), increase its 
holding of financial securities (0.8 billion), increase bank 
deposits (12.7 billion), and increase liquidity (five billion). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31470 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu112__a94010" </HT>


