<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Quarter Trade Deficit Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    First Quarter Trade Deficit Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806093194 Prague CTK in English 1911 GMT 7 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0806093194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prague June 7 (CTK) -- Czech trade during the first 
quarter was at a deficit of 2.1 billion crowns [Kc], and after 
four months the deficit diminished to 1.5 billion crowns, 
according to a government budget report that was given to 
parliament recently. 
  Czech export to advanced market economies increased by nine 
percent in the first quarter over the same period last year. 
Czech exports to Slovakia decreased by 22 percent to 15.5 
percent. Exports to former Soviet countries dropped from six to 
five percent, and to countries with transitional economies, from 
6.3 to 5.9 percent. 
  The share of machines and consumer goods was nearly 40 
percent, and the export of raw materials increased the most 
rapidly (from 6.6 to 9.8 percent). Overall, exports decreased 
by 5.6 percent (5.2 billion crowns) in the first quarter against 
the first quarter last year, and by 6.5 percent (8.2 billion 
crowns) during the first four months of 1994 in the same 
year-on-year comparison. 
  Imports in the first three months of 1994 increased by 18 
percent (almost 14 billion crowns), and by 11 percent in the 
first four months (11.6 billion crowns). Imports from advanced 
economies increased (by four percent) as well as from countries 
with transforming economies and from former Soviet states. 
Slovakia's share in Czech imports decreased from 21 to 15 
percent. Export prices grew by 2.5 percent, and import prices 
by only half a percent. 
  The surplus on the current account was at the same level as 
in the first quarter of 1993, and the surplus on the capital 
account of the payments balance was $350 million larger. 
Overall hard currency reserves were $700 million higher than in 
the first quarter last year. 

</TEXT>

