<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 9 Jun (MTI) -- Coalition talks between 
the Hungarian Socialist Party (MSZP), which won 54.15 percent of 
the votes in the May elections, and the second-placed Alliance 
of Free Democrats (SZDSZ), which won 18.14 percent of the votes, 
are to continue at 10 a.m. Sunday morning, SZDSZ Chairman Ivan 
Peto and MSZP Chairman Gyula Horn announced at a brief press 
conference following nearly three and a half hours of talks on 
Thursday. Peto said discussions were held today about various 
guarantee issues, joint parliamentary and government work, and 
related personal issues. 
  Senior experts of the two parties will hold preparatory 
talks 
of limited attendance in the days prior to Sunday's meeting. 
Peto announced that neither side in the negotiations wishes to 
provide detailed information about the content of the talks. 

