FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0906135394 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 9 Jun (MTI) -- "The election victory of 
the Socialist Party does not mean a leftist turn in Hungary, as 
the votes reflect, by and large, equal support for the three 
political trends: the left, the conservatives, and the 
liberals," President Arpad Goncz and Christian Democratic 
People's Party (KDNP) Chairman Laszlo Surjan agreed in talks at 
Budapest's parliament on Thursday. The consultation was part of 
Goncz's recent series of political discussions with 
parliamentary party leaders. 
  Surjan said he had agreed with the president on the key 
importance of a smooth transfer of governmental affairs. They 
both supposed that a coalition government would be formed. 
Regarding the KDNP's future, Surjan said the party should break 
out from the category of a religious party, and emerge in 
political life as a socially-committed party with its own system 
of values and its own message for the whole of society. 

