<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Walesa Vetoes Law Favoring Assembly Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Walesa Vetoes Law Favoring Assembly Members </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906202694 Warsaw PAP in English 1939 GMT 9 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0906202694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, June 9 -- President Lech Walesa vetoed a new 
law on the rights and duties of MPs and notified Sejm Speaker 
Jozef Oleksy about his decision on Thursday, the president's 
press office announced on Thursday. 
  The main reason of the decision was that, according to the 
proposed law, a lump money would be paid to deputies and 
senators after the expiry of their terms of office if they were 
running in the next elections, throughout the entire period 
between terms. The president contends that this would actually 
be a privilege jeopardizing those who run for the first time and 
must continue their jobs. 
  The second reason was that the proposed law converted social 
allowances paid to MPs into their regular lump payment and on 
top of that, this article would have been retroactive to June 1, 
1993, if not vetoed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

