<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Meets Romanian Counterpart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Meets Romanian Counterpart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906213694 Warsaw PAP in English 1907 GMT 9 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> LD0906213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, June 9 -- Romanian Defence Minister Gheorghe 
Tinca proposed three groups of issues on which Polish and 
Romanian military should work in further contacts at a meeting 
with his Polish counterpart Piotr Kolodziejczyk on Thursday, the 
office of the spokesman for the National Defence Ministry said 
Thursday. 
  Kolodziejczyk and Tinca, who started his three-day official 
visit to Poland on Thursday, stressed great political importance 
they attached to the meeting. The first group of issues covers 
cooperation as part of Partnership for Peace, with a special 
regard to the presence of observers and sub-units at exercises. 
Minister Tinca proposed participation of the platoon of the 
Polish alpine troops in joint exercises in Romania. 
  The second group would embrace cooperation in armament and 
between arms industries of the two countries. As for this area, 
the Romanian minister proposed to set up a mixed military 
committee to precisely specify Polish-Romanian needs in these 
areas. 
  The third group includes mutual consultations on security, 
developments in Europe, the exchange of training cadres and 
joint seminars on political questions. 
  Minister Kolodziejczyk said that all proposals made by the 
Romanian minister corresponded very well to the Polish 
understanding of the policy of security and cooperation. He 
added that Poland would be very open in all these areas. On 
Friday, the Romanian defence minister is to be received by the 
Polish president, the Sejm speaker and the prime minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

