<F P=101> Romania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Court Bans New Communist Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supreme Court Bans New Communist Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0806133994 Bucharest ROMPRES in English 0853 GMT 8 Jun 94 
-- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0806133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bucharest ROMPRES </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bucharest ROMPRES, 8/6/1994 -- Romania's Supreme 
Court, by its civil department, granted [approved] Tuesday, 7 
June, the contestations filed by several parties, associations, 
and revolutionary unions of the country against a re-birth of 
the Romanian Communist Party (RCP.) On 4 May 1994, the 
Bucharest Municipality Tribunal approved the application for 
registration of the RCP headquartered in Targu-Jiu. RCP founder 
Victor Hancu had said then that his party was not a follower of 
the former RCP. 
  After a half-hour deliberation, the Supreme Court ruled the 
decision: "To grant the contestations and the intervention 
requests, to annul the Bucharest Municipality Tribunal's 
decision of 4 May 1994, and to reject the application for 
registration of the Romanian Communist Party." 
  During the trial, the challengers' defendants have invoked 
law 51/1991 regarding Romania's national security, Article 3, 
Paragraph H, which stipulates: "The initiation, organization, 
carrying out, and support in whatever manner of totalitarian and 
extremist actions of communist, fascist, or iron-guardist 
expression is banned." 
  In his defense and in defending the party he initiated, 
Victor Hancu said: "We are not the followers of the RCP and 
most of our members had not been enrolled in the former 
Communist Party. We have no former activists in our structures." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

