<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   KDH Proposes Campaign Spending Limit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KDH Proposes Campaign Spending Limit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0906135694 Prague CTK in English 1126 GMT 9 Jun 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU0906135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava June 9 (CTK) -- The Christian Democratic 
Movement (KDH), a government coalition party, is proposing that 
a limit of ten million Slovak crowns ($300,000) be set on 
political parties' expenditure during the present election 
campaign. The media -- television, radio, the press as well as 
billboard owners -- should be obliged to inform the Central 
Electoral Commission immediately after the elections of the 
amount each political party spent on advertising, Jan 
Carnogursky said at a press conference today. The Slovak 
general elections are scheduled for September 30 and October 1. 
  If party spending on the campaign exceeded the limit by ten 
percent the state contribution to the party in question would be 
cut by the according amount, he proposed. 
  Carnogursky said the KDH had found support for the motion 
within the government coalition. He did not say when his party 
would formally submit the bill to parliament. The proposal is 
seen as being directed against Vladimir Meciar's party, the 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS), allegedly the richest 
party after presiding over many privatisation projects while in 
power. Meciar denies the allegations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

