<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Geneva Document `Far Below' Serb Expectations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Geneva Document `Far Below' Serb Expectations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906135294 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1254 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906135294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Banja Luka, 9 Jun (TANJUG) -- The document signed in 
Geneva falls far below our expectations, far below what had been 
demanded, Aleksa Buha, minister of foreign affairs of the Srpska 
republic told the SRPSKI GLAS daily in Banja Luka today. 
  "The warring sides were requested in an imperative way to 
agree to a four-month cessation of hostilities in order to reach 
a political solution in the meantime, but the Muslim side did 
not accept it." In addition, the warring sides were requested 
to negotiate without setting any conditions, but the Muslim side 
did not abide by that either, Buha said. 
  "The Geneva document has been treated as the first step 
toward reaching an agreement on the cessation of hostilities, 
while negotiations to this end will begin in a few days," Buha 
said. "Another part of the agreement contains an obigation for 
the three sides to exchange POW's on the all-for-all principle 
in the meantime; that is, before the new round of negotiations." 

</TEXT>

