<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Forced Mobilization of 1,500 Croats Ordered </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Forced Mobilization of 1,500 Croats Ordered </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU0906161894 Zagreb VJESNIK in Serbo-Croatian 9 Jun 94 p 48 </F>
<F P=103> AU0906161894 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb VJESNIK </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [HINA report: "Draft Orders for All Officials in Croatian </F>
Institutions"] 
  [Text] Mostar -- The communal secretariats of Tuzla, 
Lukavac, Zivnica, and Banovici, have in the past few days opted 
for a forced mobilization of some 1,500 Croats into the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army, Radio Herceg-Bosna reported on 
Wednesday. As reported by the correspondent of the Herceg-Bosna 
radio station in Tuzla, the military police of the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina Army 2d Corps -- after serving draft orders 
-- immediately transfers the Croats into the Bosnia-Herzegovina 
Army ranks and the military strongholds on Mt. Majevica and Mt. 
Konjuh. 
  The draft orders were served to high-ranking officials in 
all 
Croatian institutions. The Herceg-Bosna radio reports that among 
the mobilized are two members of the Croatian Democratic 
Community [HDZ] Regional Council in Tuzla, 14 presidents of HDZ 
branches, Josip Simic, president of the Croatian "Hrvatski Dom" 
Society, Drago Juric, manager of the "Sol" company, Janko 
Divkovic, president of the HDZ Youth in the Tuzla region, and 
the majority of members of the "GLASNIK HDZ SOLI" [newsletter] 
editorial board. The radio stresses that the consequence of 
this mobilization of Croats is their massive exodus from the 
region, in which they are aided by the Bosniak authorities, who 
are taking care of all the paperwork needed for leaving Tuzla. 
  Colonel-General Milivoj Petkovic, head of the Croatian 
Defense Council [HVO] General Staff in the Croatian Community of 
Herceg-Bosna, confirmed that a note on the mobilization of 
Croats had arrived from Tuzla on Tuesday. "We have informed 
Kresimir Zubak, president of the Bosnia-Herzegovina Federation, 
about this," General Petkovic told Croatian Radio Herceg-Bosna 
on Wednesday, and added that this would "create numerous 
problems." General Petkovic assessed that this was "incorrect of 
the Muslim authorities," and that it was a "calculated move." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31525 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu112_i_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-112 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lukic Protests UN Treatment of Serb Civilians </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lukic Protests UN Treatment of Serb Civilians </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906143194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1324 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, 9 Jun (TANJUG) -- Vladimir Lukic, prime 
minister of the Srpska republic, today sent a letter to Yasushi 
Akashi, the UN secretary general's envoy for former Yugoslavia, 
expressing concern over the provocative conduct by UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] soldiers in the area of Gorazde. 
  The letter reads: 
  Your Excellency, 
  I would like to express profound concern over the situation 
in the three-kilometer exclusion zone around Gorazde, created by 
hostile conduct by UN personnel toward the Serb civilian 
population. This problem was also present before, but it has 
exacerbated with the arrival of the Canadian troops in this 
area. On several occasions our civilians were ill-treated, even 
surrounded by armored vehicles and UN personnel, held at 
gun-point, had their personal belongings searched without 
authorization, and generally exposed to crude treatment. The 
most serious of all these problems is that the Canadian soldiers 
demand that the Serbs leave this zone, thus evicting them from 
their houses using brutal methods. We fear that such behavior 
is leading toward armed incidents with unforeseeable 
consequences. 
  The agreement on Gorazde does not authorize such treatment 
of 
Serb civilians. The prevailing impression among the civilians is 
that they will be gradually evicted from the area, which the UN 
will then hand over to the Muslims. Such unhealthy conditions 
can easily lead to incidents, and we believe that it is only a 
question of time when incidents will start occurring. 
  We are therefore suggesting that you forward this protest to 
the UNPROFOR military command and instruct the command to issue 
orders for the fair treatment of civilians in the 
three-kilometer exclusion zone around Gorazde. The situation is 
so serious that if no radical change takes place, we will either 
provide police escorts for our civilians or allow events to 
dictate the situation on the ground. Please treat this problem 
as one of exceptional importance. Thank you for your 
understanding. 
  Yours sincerely,Vladimir Lukic 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

