<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kovac on Improved Image of Slovakia Abroad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kovac on Improved Image of Slovakia Abroad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0906193694 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0906193694 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1630 GMT 9 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Slovak President Michal Kovac visited Slovak 
Radio today. He replied to questions by almost 100 journalists 
from Slovak Radio and other domestic and foreign media. [passage 
omitted] 
  Kovac briefed them about the international position of 
Slovakia and steps being taken to strengthen it. [passage 
omitted] 
  During his visit, the president gave a more extensive 
interview to the program "Afternoon on the Radio." We have 
excerpted the following passages: 
  [Begin Kovac recording] In the last period, I would say 
within the past four to five weeks, I have really had many 
meetings. I received positive news during almost all of them, 
at last some positive news about Slovakia, positive news about 
the fact that the government is succeeding on the home front in 
consolidating the political situation, in stabilizing it--but 
most of all, that the government has succeeded in awakening the 
necessary trust abroad. 
  Of course, I was interested in finding out why this did not 
happen earlier--what the reasons were for our image not 
developing positively and why representatives of individual 
states were ignoring Slovakia when talking on various occasion 
about possible incorporation into the West European structures. 
Regrettably--and this was for me a very unpleasant discovery 
that I have to bring into the open--this was mostly connected 
with the persona of the [former] prime minister rather than with 
the overall activity of the [former] government. 
  At this point, it is not up to me to analyze the reasons for 
this state of affairs. I am only stating the fact, and I 
consider it necessary for the former prime minister himself to 
analyze, possibly together with others, the reasons for that 
situation. I think Slovakia cannot solve its problems without 
gaining the necessary trust in the East as well as in the West, 
in the United States, Canada, and elsewhere. Furthermore, I 
wish to say that the present government, which has succeeded in 
gaining a good reputation, should be aware that it has to go on 
fighting to keep it. It is not sufficient to gain trust for the 
time being. It is a matter that should continue because it may 
also easily disappear. I firmly believe that the individual 
ministers are aware of this and also that their activities 
abroad have contributed to the more positive image Slovakia has 
finally achieved. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

