<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kontic on Economy, `Short-Term' Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kontic on Economy, `Short-Term' Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006165494 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1440 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1006165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Serbo-Croatian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Belgrade, 10 Jun (TANJUG) -- Federal Prime 
Minister Radoje Kontic said today that an extraordinary 
parliamentiary session would be justified only if implementation 
of the economic stabilization program was threatened. 
  Speaking at a regular news conference he said that the 
government will closely monitor the implementation of this 
year's economic policy and, depending on the situation, would 
decide whether or not to convene an extraordinary session. 
[passage omitted] 
  Answering a question about the cease-fire in the former 
Bosnia- Herzegovina and the decision of the House of 
Representatives of the U.S. Congress on the lifting of the 
embargo on arms imports for the Muslims, Kontic said that a 
short-term cease-fire, as well as the decision on lifting the 
embargo, are encouraging Muslims to persist in the war option. 
He added that some of President Clinton's statements that the 
arms embargo will not be lifted were encouraging. 
  Asked about the army and police allegedly stepping up their 
activities in Raska, about which the Muslim National Council of 
Sandzak has informed foreign journalists, Kontic said that this 
was not true and that such claims are spread in order to exert 
pressure on Serbia, primarily from abroad. He added that he had 
given instructions for an investigation to be carried out. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

