<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Krajisnik: Muslims Will Not Agree to Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Krajisnik: Muslims Will Not Agree to Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206145494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1427 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Novi Sad, June 12 (TANJUG) -- President of the 
parliament of the Bosnian Serb republic (R.S.) Momcilo 
Krajisnik, with reference to the latest one-month ceasefire 
signed in Geneva, has stated that the Muslims will not agree to 
any peace irrespective of its limited length. Krajisnik said 
this in an interview to be published in Monday's DNEVNIK daily 
of Novi Sad. He added that perhaps it was better that a 
short-range truce was signed in Geneva. 
  "Had they accepted the Serb proposal on a year-long 
cessation 
of hostilities," said he, "they would have presented themselves 
to the world as the fighters for peace, but, essentially, they 
do not give up their offensive actions against Serb territories." 
  Geneva talks on the overall cessation of hostilities in 
Bosnia ended on June 7 in signinig a statement on a one-month 
cessation of combat activities, based on the Muslim-Croat 
proposal. In commenting on a territorial division map drawn by 
the "contact group" in Geneva, Krajisnik said that this had 
concerned the fulfilment of the megalomaniac demands by Croats 
and Muslims to be given nearly the entire western Bosnia and 
good parts of northern and eastern Bosnia. 
  "Of course, it is out of the question that we shall agree to 
give the places where genocide of Serb people was committed in 
the past two wars," said Krajisnik. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

