<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Spokesman Details Brcko Truce Violation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Spokesman Details Brcko Truce Violation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1206195294 Paris AFP in English 1932 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1206195294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, June 12 (AFP) -- Rockets slammed into 
the northern Serb-held town of Brcko on Sunday [12 June], but 
Bosnia's fragile two-day-old truce was otherwise holding, a UN 
spokesman said. Five or six rockets from an unknown source fell 
at midday in the first truce violation at Brcko since the 
UN-brokered ceasefire came into effect on Friday, Commander Eric 
Chaperon said. 
  "However, the overall situation remains calm, with a 
slightly 
higher level of activity than in the morning," he said in 
mid-afternoon. [passage omitted] Chaperon said earlier he did 
not know where the shells had been fired from. 
  Brcko commands a narrow strip of land across northern 
Bosnia-Herzegovina that forms a crucial supply line for Serbs 
between their stronghold of Banja Luka in the west and Serbia to 
the east. The area, known as the Posavina corridor, has seen a 
build-up by both Bosnian army and separatist Serb forces in the 
past two months. 
  Chaperon said UN troops recorded 11 detonations at the 
northeastern town of Srebrenik, a few detonations at Dastansko, 
in central Bosnia, and 16 mortar rounds at Ribnica, a Bosnian 
army position in the north of the republic. A UN patrol at 
Gorazde in eastern Bosnia "came under light arms fire from 
Bosnian Serb forces," Chaperon added. 
  In the northwestern Moslem pocket of Bihac, the situation 
was 
calm Sunday after attacks a day earlier by Bosnian army forces 
in which they recovered territory captured by secessionists 
loyal to maverick Moslem leader Fikret Abdic, Chaperon said. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

