<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Confirms Croatian `Offensive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Confirms Croatian `Offensive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306102094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 0922 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1306102094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 13 (TANJUG) -- UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Forces] representative in Sarajevo confirmed Sunday 
night [12 June] that the forces of Bosnian Croats launched an 
offensive against the Serbs in Bosnia in the north of the former 
Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. As the UPI news agency 
reported, he specified that at least five projectiles were fired 
from multiple rocket launchers Sunday on Brcko, a Serb town in 
northern Bosnia. 
  This action by Bosnian Croats surprised the U.N., said the 
UNPROFOR representative. According to the Bosnian Serbs' 
military sources, five civilians, including a child and a Serb 
soldier, were wounded when from the territory of neighboring 
Croatia 8 projectiles were fired from the multiple rocket 
launchers on civilian targets in Brcko. 
  This was the eighth artillery attack on Brcko over the past 
month, and the fifth from the territory controlled by the 
forcibly seceded former Yugoslav Republic of Croatia. The 
attacks killed a total of seven and wounded 46 people either on 
the street or at home. 
  The attack on Brcko came in spite a four-week ceasefire, 
concluded last Wednesday in Geneva, which came into force on 
Friday at noon between the Moslem-Croatian federation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and the Bosnian Serb republic (R.S.). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

