<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Muslims Confirm Readiness To Exchange POW's </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Muslims Confirm Readiness To Exchange POW's </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1206173994 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1720 GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1206173994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Sarajevo, June 12 (TANJUG) -- Bosnian Serb 
parliamentary Speaker Momcilo Krajisnik has stated that the Serb 
side has received assurances from the Moslems that they are 
willing to exchange all remaining POWs as agreed on Saturday [11 
June]. Krajisnik made the statement on Sunday after Bosnian 
Serbs and Moslems had resumed talks at Sarajevo airport on 
prisoner exchanges. 
  After the first round of talks on Saturday, the two sides 
agreed to complete the lists of POWs held by the International 
Committee of the Red Cross [ICRC] to include those captured in 
the recent fighting on Mt. Ozren in the north and around Gorazde 
in the southeast. The exchanges are to take place at Sarajevo 
airport, in Gorazde and at Satorovici near Brcko in northern 
Bosnia. 
  The two sides also agreed that a meeting be held on 
Wednesday 
by local representatives to exchange information about the 
missing. At the next round of talks on Friday, the two sides 
will negotiate dates for the exchanges. 
  An ICRC spokesman said in Geneva on Friday the organization 
estimated that Bosnian Moslems and Croats were holding about 450 
persons prisoner and that the Serbs were holding approximately 
the same number of prisoners. The one-month truce which the 
Bosnian Serb Republic and the Moslem-Croat federation in Bosnia 
signed on Wednesday envisages an immediate release of all 
prisoners, including POWs. The truce came into effect at noon 
on Friday. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

