<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bogdanovic Views Clinton Remarks on Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bogdanovic Views Clinton Remarks on Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006182694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1752 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006182694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, June 10 (TANJUG) -- Yugoslav Parliament 
Upper House President Radmilo Bogdanovic assessed on Friday that 
the time for easing the sanctions against the Federal Republic 
of Yugoslavia (F.R.Y.) was approaching, judging by statements 
supporting a cessation of hostilities in the former Yugoslavia 
made by U.S. President Bill Clinton and the European Union. 
Bogdanovic said this during talks with representatives of the 
"Min" mechanical engineering factory in Nis (Serbia). 
  The United Nations in May 1992 imposed comprehensive 
sanctions against Yugoslavia for its alleged involvement in the 
civil war in the former Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  President Clinton was actually threatening the Bosnian 
Moslems when he spoke of the lifting of the sanctions against 
Yugoslavia, according to Slobodan Rakitic, opposition Depos 
[Democratic Movement of Serbia] bloc deputy in the Yugoslav 
Parliament. "The sanctions against Yugoslavia will be softened 
if a Moslem-Croat federation rejects a peace plan," a statement 
signed by Rakitic on behalf of a group of Depos MPs said. 
  Clinton's statement could be understood as a kind of 
confession that neither the introduction of sanctions had 
depended on Serbia, Montenegro and the Bosnian Serb Republic 
(R.S.), the statement also said. "If the lifting of the 
sanctions is announced now as punishing the Moslems for 
disobedience, then the introduction was a reward to a 
Moslem-Croat coalition for their war option," the announcement 
said. 
  Delegations of the Moslem-Croat Federation and of the 
Bosnian 
Serb republic signed on Wednesday in Geneva a one-month 
ceasefire accord, althouth the Serb side was for a one-year 
cessation of hostilities, estimating that a one-month ceasefire 
is too short for finding a political settlement to end the 
Bosnian war. 

</TEXT>

