<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   War Called `Option' in Recovering Areas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    War Called `Option' in Recovering Areas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1006204294 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1940 GMT 10 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1006204294 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, June 10 (TANJUG) -- Zagreb will not shrink 
from "war option as an ultimate means" to re-establish its 
authority in the U.N. Protected Area (UNPA) on the territory of 
the former Yugoslav Republic of Croatia, said Jure Radic, head 
of the presidential office of Franjo Tudjman, Friday. 
  "This will be done through consistent peacemaking policy", 
but "we do not rule out war option either as an ultimate means," 
Radic, secretary-general of the ruling Croatian Democratic Union 
(HDZ), told a rally in Delnice. 
  According to Croatian media, Radic warned that Croatia this 
time openly pointed out that this was the "last unproductive 
mandate of the U.N. Protection Force (UNPROFOR). If the U.N. 
forces were not deployed on the internationally-recognized 
Croatian borders, the Croatian Army would," he said. 
"Cypriotization of Croatia is out of question" as well as the 
possibility of part of Croatia "becomimg some other state," 
Radic stressed. 
  The UNPA in Croatia matches the Republic of Serb Krajina 
(R.S.K.), which was in 1991 proclaimed by the Serbs on the 
territories where they are majority population, in response to 
Croatia's forcible secession from the former Yugoslavia and 
downgrading the status of the Serbs in the new state of Croatia 
from a constituent people to one of a natioanl minority. 
  Croatia does not recognize the R.S.K. and has attempted four 
times to forcibly return it under Zagreb's authority. The 
Krajina Serbs do not want to give up their independence, 
claiming that their state is legitinate, being created by 
breaking-up of the former Yugoslavia and that they, since they 
were a constituent people in the former state, have the right to 
self-determination. 
  Croatian President Tudjman has also on several occasions in 
recent months announced that Zagreb will re-establish authority 
in the entire territory of the former Yugoslav Republic of 
Croatia by force if not through negotiations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-31629 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu113_p_94001" </HT>


