<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Schmoegnerova Outlines Macroeconomic Aims </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Schmoegnerova Outlines Macroeconomic Aims </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1306152994 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1306152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1000 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=105> Slovak </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Deputy Prime Minister Brigita Schmoegnerova 
briefed journalists at a regular news conference about this 
morning's signing by the representatives of the government and 
the Slovak National Bank of the letter of intent for the IMF's 
standby loan. The letter of intent was sent to IMF Managing 
Director Michel Camdessus. The attention of journalists at the 
brief news conference focused on the commitments arising from 
this document for Slovakia. Our radio was represented by Ivan 
Samel. 
  [begin Schmoegnerova recording] The letter of intent 
incorporates economic policy intentions for 1994 and 1995, which 
include a budget deficit of 4 percent for 1994 and a GDP rise of 
3 percent for 1995. Our further aim is to hold inflation at 10 
percent in 1994 and at 8 percent in 1995. Another of our 
macroeconomic aims is to maintain the internal convertibility in 
1994 and 1995, with the proviso that, by 1 January 1996, we will 
have prepared a so-called full internal convertibility of the 
current account of the balance of payments. 
  Apart from these macroeconomic intentions, or rather the 
government economic policy aims, the letter of intent also 
contains measures related to financial policies, the external 
financial sector, privatization, the financial restructuring of 
enterprises, and the building up of the financial sector. 
[passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

